<?xml version='1.0' encoding='utf-8'?>
<chapter xml:id="FTC" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>The Fundamental Theorem of Calculus</title>
<p>
Suppose a point <m>P</m> begins at <m>x_0</m> and traces out a line segment of some unkno<!-- wn length, <m>x</m>.  We partition the line segment between <m>x_0</m> and <m>x</m> into subintervals as seen in figure . . . -->
<!-- If the symbol <m>\Delta x_1</m> represents the first subinterval of -->
<!-- <m>x</m>, <m>\Delta x_2</m> represents the second subinterval, and in general if <m>\Delta{x_i}</m> represents the <m>i</m>th subinterval of <m>x</m> then clearly the length of the line segment is  -->
<!-- <md> -->
<!-- <mrow>\Delta{x_1}+\Delta{x_2}+\Delta{x_3} +\cdots +\Delta{x_{n-1}}+\Delta{x_n}</mrow> -->
<!-- <mrow> = (x_1-x_0)+(x_2-x_2)+(x_3-x_2) +\cdots + -->
<!-- (x_{n-1}-x_{n-2})+(x_n-x_{n-1})</mrow> -->
<!-- <mrow>=x_n-x_0</mrow> -->
<!-- </md> -->
<!-- If the subintervals are all the same length, say <m>\Delta{x}</m>, then we no longer need the subscripts to distinguish them. This makes our notation a little less cumbersome, as follows: -->
<!-- <md> -->
<!-- <mrow>\underbrace{\Delta{x}+\Delta{x}+\cdots{}+\Delta{x}}_{<m>n</m>\text{ copies}}=x_n-x_0</mrow> -->
<!-- </md> -->
</p>
/chapter>

